            <instruction>
                <text>
                    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Patch Major Vulnerabilities! &lt;/strong&gt;This is possible that users select weak passwords due to lack of effort and motivation or misunderstanding of threats or problem to memorize strong passwords.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/21749080.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Users need help! &lt;/strong&gt;81% of hacking-related breaches leveraged either stolen and/or weak passwords.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://enterprise.verizon.com/resources/reports/2017_dbir.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why helping users is vital to have strong passwords! &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Make password requirements visible upfront, allow users to unmask the password, and show a strength meter to users.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;In your software make sure that users who forget their passwords can easily reset it.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/build-a-simple-password-strength-checker--net-7565&quot;&gt;Build a Simple Password Strength Checker&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Set a default value for all Password Quality Scale fields (IBM)&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Password Quality Scale&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/en/SSKTMJ_8.5.3/com.ibm.help.domino.admin85.doc/H_PASSWORD_QUALITY_SCALE_UNDERSTANDING_AND_SETTING_DEFAULTS_STEPS.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
                </text>
                <attachments>
                    <attachment id="acces-q70p1" mime="image/jpeg"><content filename="acces-q70p1.jpg" xml:lang="de"></content>
                    </attachment>
                </attachments>
            </instruction>
        </question>
        <question id="acces-q80" type="A" hidden="false">
            <text>When do you force your users to change their passwords?</text>
            <attachments/>
            <options correct="acces-q80o1">
                <option id="acces-q80o1">
                    <text>WE FORCE A CHANGE ONCE EVERY MONTH</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q80o2">
                    <text>WE FORCE A CHANGE ONCE EVERY THIRD MONTH</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
            </options>
            <listeners/>
            <metadata key="scores">
                <mvalue key="acces-q80o1">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
                <mvalue key="acces-q80o2">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <metadata key="nextQid">
                <mvalue key="default">
                    <stringValue>acces-q90</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <instruction>
                <text>
                    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Users must change their passwords!&lt;/strong&gt; Once or twice a year for the significant accounts and those do not have 2-factor authentication. Also, If they have easy-to-guess passwords or if there is an indication or suspicion of compromise.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.psafe.com/en/blog/often-need-change-passwords&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why not use regular password changing for all accounts!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Regular password changing (every 30, 60 or 90 days) can harms rather than improve security. Users tend to select new passwords with similar patterns that only have minor variations of the old one. So, no real advantage as stolen passwords are generally exploited immediately. Hackers cite &amp;ldquo;remembering and changing passwords&amp;rdquo; as a top source of cyber fatigue.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/458857/Password_guidance_-_simplifying_your_approach.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The most frequently attempted login names and passwords for attackers against IoT devices&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.symantec.com/content/dam/symantec/docs/reports/istr-23-2018-en.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
                </text>
                <attachments>
                    <attachment id="acces-q80p1" mime="image/jpeg"><content filename="acces-q80p1.jpg" xml:lang="de"></content>
                    </attachment>
                </attachments>
            </instruction>
        </question>
        <question id="acces-q90" type="A" hidden="false">
            <text>Are the passwords sent encrypted between client and the server?</text>
            <attachments/>
            <options correct="acces-q90o1">
                <option id="acces-q90o1">
                    <text>YES, PASSWORDS ARE ALWAYS ENCRYPTED</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q90o2">
                    <text>MOST PASSWORDS ARE ENCRYPTED</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q90o3">
                    <text>SOME PASSWORDS ARE ENCRYPTED</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q90o4">
                    <text>NO, PASSWORDS ARE NOT ENCRYPTED</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
            </options>
            <listeners/>
            <metadata key="scores">
                <mvalue key="acces-q90o1">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
                <mvalue key="acces-q90o2">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <metadata key="nextQid">
                <mvalue key="default">
                    <stringValue>acces-q100</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <instruction>
                <text>
                    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keep Hackers at bay! &lt;/strong&gt;For protecting your data against unauthorised users, it should be encrypted when transmitted across a network.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://security.berkeley.edu/data-encryption-transit-guideline&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How to encrypt passwords! &lt;/strong&gt;Passwords can be encrypted through one-way format (prevents clear passwords from even administrators) or two-way format (decrypting passwords when returning to an authorized client).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;One-way formats such as: Salted SHA-1, MD5&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Two-way formats such as: AES&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/en/ssw_ibm_i_71/rzahy/rzahypwdencrypt.htm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;iframe width=&quot;560&quot; height=&quot;315&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/8ZtInClXe1Q&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allow=&quot;accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Multi-factor authentication and encryption are biggest hacker obstacles&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://thycotic.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/BlackHa_Hacker_Survey_Report_2017.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
                </text>
                <attachments>
                    <attachment id="acces-q90p1" mime="image/jpeg"><content filename="acces-q90p1.jpg" xml:lang="de"></content>
                    </attachment>
                </attachments>
            </instruction>
        </question>
        <question id="acces-q100" type="A" hidden="false">
            <text>Do the software systems you develop limit the number of unsuccessful attempts to login?</text>
            <attachments/>
            <options correct="acces-q100o1">
                <option id="acces-q100o1">
                    <text>YES, THEY LIMIT THE ATTEMPTS</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q100o2">
                    <text>SOME SYSTEMS LIMIT THE ATTEMPTS</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q100o3">
                    <text>NO, THEY DO NOT LIMIT THE ATTEMPTS</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
            </options>
            <listeners/>
            <metadata key="scores">
                <mvalue key="acces-q100o1">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
                <mvalue key="acces-q100o2">
                    <stringValue>50</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <metadata key="nextQid">
                <mvalue key="default">
                    <stringValue>acces-q110</stringValue>
                </mvalue>
            </metadata>
            <instruction>
                <text>
                    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Block Brute Force Attacks!&lt;/strong&gt; It is a common threat web developers should consider. Hackers may apply scripts to attempt a brute-force attack.&amp;nbsp; They try a lot of combinations of usernames and passwords systematically to find the right one.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How to avoid Brute Force Attacks! &lt;/strong&gt;Some of the common approaches are:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Locking down accounts after a defined number of failed login attempts. However, it can cause DoS (denial of service) by locking&amp;nbsp;multiple accounts.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Making random progressive pauses when checking a password after a few incorrect login attempts. However, it can bother legitimate users.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;returning an &quot;HTTP 401 error&quot; code with a password failure&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;After some failed login attempts, you can ask the user not only for the username and password but also to answer a secret question.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Combination of several approaches.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Forcing users to apply strong passwords&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;Providing the possibility of 2-factor authentication&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Blocking_Brute_Force_Attacks&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;iframe width=&quot;560&quot; height=&quot;315&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/nkQAfQ5pwtk&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allow=&quot;accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;
                </text>
                <attachments>
                </attachments>
            </instruction>
        </question>
        <question id="acces-q110" type="A" hidden="false">
            <text>Do you implement the principles of least privilege in your access control process?</text>
            <attachments/>
            <options correct="acces-q110o1">
                <option id="acces-q110o1">
                    <text>YES,  WE IMPLEMENT ALL THE PRINCIPLES</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q110o2">
                    <text>WE IMPLEMENT MOST OF THE PRINCIPLES</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q110o3">
                    <text>WE IMPLEMENT A FEW OF THE PRINCIPLES</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
                <option id="acces-q110o4">
                    <text>NO, WE DO NOT IMPLEMENT THE PRINCIPLES</text>
                    <attachments></attachments>
                </option>
            </options>
            <listeners/>
            <instruction>
                <text>
                    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reduce the effect of successful attacks! &lt;/strong&gt;Each user, process, and program should be assigned to the minimum level of users rights (only sufficient access). For instance, if an account needs to pull records from a database must not have admin rights.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.cybersecurity.my/properties_v3/images/guidelines/03%20SMEs.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why Principles Of Least Privilege!&lt;/strong&gt; It can improve the cybersecurity level in your company by reducing the risk of unauthorized access to critical systems or important data.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Improving the security level&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Decreasing attack surface&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Limiting malware propagation&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Improving audit readiness&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://digitalguardian.com/blog/what-principle-least-privilege-polp-best-practice-information-security-and-compliance&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Principles Of Least Privilege for SMEs! &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Few employees require extensive administrator rights&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Only grant as many rights to an employee as are necessary to do their work.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Disable the rights to install any software&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;a title=&quot;Information security checklist for SMEs - Melde- und Analysestelle Informationssicherung MELANI&quot; href=&quot;https://www.melani.admin.ch/dam/melani/en/dokumente/2018/04/180525_MerkBlatt-Info-Sicherheit-KMU-en.pdf.download.pdf/180525_MerkBlatt-Info-Sicherheit-KMU-en.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;More info ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;iframe src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/bY4qZH3Mpn8&quot; width=&quot;560&quot; height=&quot;315&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen=&quot;allowfullscreen&quot;&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
                </text>
                <attachments>
                </attachments>
            </instruction>
        </question>
